Section1.Para:
In the United States, African-American men are at the greatest risk of developing prostate cancer and approximately 20% (or one in five) of African-American men are diagnosed in their lifetime (assuming a lifespan of 85 years; 
                www.seer.cancer.gov

              ). Similarly, one out of six non-Hispanic white men, one in seven Hispanic men, and one in nine Asian/Pacific Islander men develop prostate cancer. Globally, prostate cancer is more common in the Americas, Western and Northern Europe, South Africa, Australia, and New Zealand. Asian and North African countries have historically lower rates of prostate cancer incidence.
